events.name: Pints & Cloud Platform
events.description:
• What we'll do:
Join us for a bi-weekly casual meetup, where we discuss the latest Google Cloud Platform offerings, networking with other cloud engineers and backend developers, and promote upcoming seminars and workshops! For this first go around we will spend some time getting to know one another and discussing what we as a collective would like to explore with GDG Cloud Tucson.

• What to bring:
A laptop is always recommended with GDG Cloud Tucson events. If you have dietary restrictions, please notify an organizer so we may do our best to accommodate (you may also bring your own snacks).

• Important to know:
Attendees are subject to GDG Community Guidelines and our code of conduct, accessible via: https://developers.google.com/programs/community/gdg/resources/

(Note: Location is likely yet not certain. An update will follow with finalized location details)

events.name: Next '18 Extended Tucson
events.description:
Join us for this year's Google Cloud Next Extended event, hosted by GDG Cloud Tucson! We are excited to bring together our cloud engineers, software developers, and entrepreneurs interested in the latest cloud technology announcements.

During the event, we'll be hosting:
- a quick introduction/networking activity
- a video recap of the Day 1 (announcements) and Day 3 (developer focused) keynotes
- a video demo of how to build an application on Google Cloud in 15 minutes by Kelsey Hightower, a Google Cloud Developer Advocate
- 1-2 short run format talks/customer demos (speakers TBA)
- a hosted hands-on-lab with Quiklabs
- Q&A/panel discussion (time permitting)

As an attendee, you'll receive:
- 1-2 months complimentary access to Qwiklabs, a $55+ value, where you can play around with the real Google Cloud platform without a billing profile, and earn badges for your LinkedIn profile or resume
- 1 month free access to Google Cloud Specializations on Coursera, which is incredibly useful if you are interested in getting certified on Google Cloud
- random drawing for prizes (Google Daydream View VR headsets, Google Home Minis)

We recommend bringing:
- a laptop or device with a dedicated keyboard
- power cable/battery bank
- headphones, if you'd prefer to do labs solo

---

Food and beverage will be provided (vendors TBA). If you have any allergen/dietary considerations, please let us know ASAP so that we can best accommodate.

---

If you would like to apply to be a speaker or provide a demo of how you use Google cloud, please email a brief proposal to: [masked]

---

Shout out to Connect Coworking for providing us with an awesome venue, and for Google for providing support for this event <3
events.how_to_find_us: Please use the door on 5th Ave facing the AC Marriot/Playground. Street parking at meters/30-minute loading zones are free after 5p. There are two City of Tucson parking garages, as well as a streetcar station, within walking distance.

events.name: GDG Cloud DevFest '18: UA Women's Hackathon Edition
events.description:
This year, we are happy to support the University of Arizona Women's Hackathon! Here's a little bit about their event:

"Join us for a weekend of food, fun, learning, and hacking! We are proud to offer a diverse set of workshops and childcare for participants during workshop hours. This free event provides an opportunity for participants of all levels of technical expertise to collaboratively develop tech-driven projects over the course of two days. All are encouraged to attend — no computer programming experience required."

At 2:15p, join us for a special workshop hosted by Andrew Slattery:

"Step into the future of computing with an interactive workshop, hosted by your local Google Cloud Developer Group. You'll run code without a server, use computer vision to tell a person's mood, and join us for a game of "whack-a-pod," where you can become a traditional sysadmin's worst nightmare..."

And afterwords, we'll be hosting office hours to help attendees with cloud related workflows and deployments.

Due to security considerations, you will need to check-in prior to entering the workshop and hackathon event space.

For more information on the UA Women's Hackathon, please visit: https://womenshackathon.arizona.edu/
events.how_to_find_us: This event is hosted in conjunction with the UA Women's Hackathon at the Science & Engineering Library on the University of Arizona campus.

events.name: Hack Arizona takeover - Kubernetes Cloud Study Jam
events.description:
WHO:
All Hack Arizona educational programming (including this workshop) are free and open to the public! All skill levels are welcome. A laptop is *strongly* recommended for participation in the hands-on-labs.

Please note that this workshop has been promoted within Hack Arizona, which is expecting more than 1,000 university students in attendance. In the event of overflow, we will work with event staff to coordinate additional seating.

WHAT:
Join organizers Andrew Slattery and Charlie Maxwell, as we explore the amazing world of Kubernetes!

- Primer on the basics of cloud native computing
- Introduction to Kubernetes and container orchestration
- Live Demos
- Hands-on-Labs
- All attendees will receive 30 days access to Qwiklabs, the hands-on-lab resource provided by Google Cloud (works for existing accounts too!)
- There will be a prize raffle near the end of the allotted workshop time

WHERE:
This event will be hosted in the Integrated Learning Center, room 117. Please refer to the "How to find us" guide and map below for more information. If you find yourself lost, please ask on-site event staff and volunteers for guidance.

PARKING:
Per Hack Arizona staff, "Main Gate, Tyndall, and 6th St. Garages are all free throughout the weekend. Parking is not available in Second St. or Cherry Ave. Garages."

CODE OF CONDUCT:
All event attendees are subject to Hack Arizona's code of conduct (https://static.mlh.io/docs/mlh-code-of-conduct.pdf), as well as GDG Cloud Tucson's (https://github.com/GDGCloudTucson/Ramp/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)
events.how_to_find_us:
Update 01/19/2018:

We have been assigned the Integrated Learning Center #117. The best way to access this area is by heading to the Main Library, and following the posted signage to the ILC. Accessible entrance is available through the Main Library.

events.name: Cloud DevFest Tucson '19

venue.name: Historic Brings Coworking | Downtown Tucson Office Space & Conference Rooms

events.description:
Have you ever wanted to develop, deploy, and maintain your own web or mobile application?

How about creating an API for other developers to leverage your unique data or technology?

Or maybe you're just curious about "the cloud," and want to get hands-on experience from experienced professionals?

Then you're in luck -- join us Saturday September 28th downtown for Cloud DevFest Tucson 2019!

As this is our inaugural Cloud DevFest event, we're waiving ticket fees, so bring a friend or colleague!

Topics we'll cover in our speaker sessions and workshops:
- How to deploy your application to the cloud
- How to build a continuous integration/delivery (CI/D) pipeline
- How containers work
- What is a progressive web application (PWA), and why you should care?
- Using Firebase to prototype your ideas
- Taking Firebase into production
- Breaking down serverless computing
- First hand recollection of launching an app powered by Firebase and Google Cloud
- NEW: Machine Learning Study Jam hosted by Dan from GDG Tucson

--

Speakers TBA shortly.

If you are interested in presenting a lightning talk, or demonstrate how you're using the cloud in your project, please complete our Call for Papers (CFP) form here (https://forms.gle/q6UiUgUJ6WYyxMAo8), or reach out to us at [masked].

--

Attendees are subject to GDG Community Guidelines and our code of conduct, accessible via: https://github.com/GDGCloudTucson/Ramp/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md

--

We recommend bringing:
- a laptop or device with a dedicated keyboard, and necessary power cable/banks for use throughout the event

--

Lunch and refreshments will be provided at no additional charge (vendors TBA). If you have any allergen/dietary considerations, please let us know ASAP so that we can best accommodate.

---

Special thanks to:
- Historic Brings Coworking space for providing venue support.
events.how_to_find_us:
Just a short walk from the streetcar on Broadway, bus stops on 6th Ave., TuGo at Armory Park, and plenty of street parking that is free on the weekends on the surrounding streets. 

Signs to the main event space will be posted. Elevator is available.

Join us for a bi-weekly casual meetup, where we discuss the latest Google Cloud Platform offerings, networking with other cloud engineers and backend developers, and promote upcoming seminars and workshops!

• What to bring:
A laptop is always recommended with GDG Cloud Tucson events. If you have dietary restrictions, please notify an organizer so we may do our best to accommodate (you may also bring your own snacks).

• Important to know:
Attendees are subject to GDG Community Guidelines and our code of conduct, accessible via: https://developers.google.com/programs/community/gdg/resources/
